# House Price Prediction Using Support Vector Machine (SVM)
## Introduction
Predicting house prices is an essential task in the real estate market. The aim of this project is to develop a machine learning model that can effectively predict house prices based on various features. ## Step-by-Step Explanation
# Import Necessary Libraries
We begin by importing the necessary libraries for data manipulation, machine learning, and evaluation. This includes pandas for data handling, NumPy for numerical operations, Matplotlib and Seaborn for visualization, and several modules from scikit-learn for machine learning tasks.

# Create the Dataset
The dataset used in this project is the "housing.csv," which contains various features related to houses and their prices. The dataset is loaded into a pandas DataFrame for easier manipulation.

# Separate Features and Target Variable
We separate the features (input variables) and the target variable (output variable).

# Split the Data
The dataset is split into training and testing sets with a 70-30 ratio to ensure a sufficient amount of data for both training and evaluating the model.

# Standardize the Data
The features are standardized using the StandardScaler from scikit-learn to ensure that they have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. This helps in improving the performance of the SVM model.

# Train the SVM Model
We train a Support Vector Machine (SVM) with various kernel functions on the training data. SVMs are powerful regressors that work well with high-dimensional data, making them suitable for predicting house prices.

# Test the Model
The trained SVM model is then used to predict the prices of the test data.
